1
00:00:00,000 --> 00:00:01,260
I want you to imagine

2
00:00:01,260 --> 00:00:03,660
that you suddenly became rich overnight.

3
00:00:03,660 --> 00:00:06,060
Maybe one of your
investments went to the moon,

4
00:00:06,060 --> 00:00:08,400
a side hustle you started took off,

5
00:00:08,400 --> 00:00:10,020
you got a large inheritance,

6
00:00:10,020 --> 00:00:11,820
or you won the lottery.

7
00:00:11,820 --> 00:00:13,860
Believe it or not, many
of you will find yourself

8
00:00:13,860 --> 00:00:15,510
in one of these scenarios,

9
00:00:15,510 --> 00:00:18,270
so this video was recommended
to you for a reason.

10
00:00:18,270 --> 00:00:21,240
I mean, let's take the
most unlikely option:

11
00:00:21,240 --> 00:00:22,260
winning the lottery.

12
00:00:22,260 --> 00:00:25,230
This channel's had over 1.5 billion views.

13
00:00:25,230 --> 00:00:27,750
Statistically, that's
enough that a few of you

14
00:00:27,750 --> 00:00:30,060
have already won the
jackpot on the lottery,

15
00:00:30,060 --> 00:00:31,080
and the odds say

16
00:00:31,080 --> 00:00:33,300
at least a couple more
of you watching right now

17
00:00:33,300 --> 00:00:34,410
will win in the future.

18
00:00:34,410 --> 00:00:36,510
So that's a good thing, right?

19
00:00:36,510 --> 00:00:39,420
Well, actually, when
you suddenly get rich,

20
00:00:39,420 --> 00:00:41,880
you're far more likely to
lose friends and family,

21
00:00:41,880 --> 00:00:43,980
have a greater risk of substance abuse,

22
00:00:43,980 --> 00:00:45,810
and finally, divorce.

23
00:00:45,810 --> 00:00:47,460
Most people who get rich fast

24
00:00:47,460 --> 00:00:49,470
have never actually built wealth before

25
00:00:49,470 --> 00:00:52,470
and have absolutely no idea
how to manage everything.

26
00:00:52,470 --> 00:00:54,840
So here are the seven
things you need to do

27
00:00:54,840 --> 00:00:56,610
when you suddenly get rich,

28
00:00:56,610 --> 00:00:58,257
from a millionaire businessman.

29
00:00:58,257 --> 00:01:01,440
(rousing music)

30
00:01:01,440 --> 00:01:02,580
I know it might be tempting

31
00:01:02,580 --> 00:01:04,290
to go screaming it from the rooftops

32
00:01:04,290 --> 00:01:06,480
and rubbing it in your enemy's faces,

33
00:01:06,480 --> 00:01:10,440
but the absolute best move is
staying as quiet as possible

34
00:01:10,440 --> 00:01:11,520
and telling no one.

35
00:01:11,520 --> 00:01:14,580
Privacy is really your main
priority at this point.

36
00:01:14,580 --> 00:01:17,700
You want to be what is
known as stealth rich.

37
00:01:17,700 --> 00:01:21,873
A guy called Jack Whittaker
won $314.9 million

38
00:01:21,873 --> 00:01:24,480
from the Powerball in 2002.

39
00:01:24,480 --> 00:01:25,350
At the time,

40
00:01:25,350 --> 00:01:28,650
it was the largest jackpot
ever won by a single ticket.

41
00:01:28,650 --> 00:01:30,870
He was the opposite of stealth rich.

42
00:01:30,870 --> 00:01:32,820
He went around telling everyone

43
00:01:32,820 --> 00:01:35,670
and even became famous for
giving money to strangers

44
00:01:35,670 --> 00:01:36,780
that asked him for help.

45
00:01:36,780 --> 00:01:38,790
He gave away millions to the church

46
00:01:38,790 --> 00:01:41,340
and even bought his friends
new cars and houses.

47
00:01:41,340 --> 00:01:44,910
Now, you're probably thinking
he sounds like a lovely guy,

48
00:01:44,910 --> 00:01:47,790
maybe a bit silly, but he had a good heart

49
00:01:47,790 --> 00:01:50,100
and good things come to kind people.

50
00:01:50,100 --> 00:01:52,650
Well, that couldn't be
further from the truth.

51
00:01:52,650 --> 00:01:54,060
His wife divorced him,

52
00:01:54,060 --> 00:01:55,500
friends abandoned him,

53
00:01:55,500 --> 00:01:58,170
and his granddaughter,
who he spoilt with money,

54
00:01:58,170 --> 00:02:00,210
tragically died from an overdose.

55
00:02:00,210 --> 00:02:03,240
He later admitted that
being too much of a nice guy

56
00:02:03,240 --> 00:02:05,940
destroyed both his fortune and his family.

57
00:02:05,940 --> 00:02:09,210
So now you understand the
importance of being stealth rich,

58
00:02:09,210 --> 00:02:10,560
how do you actually do it?

59
00:02:10,560 --> 00:02:12,930
Well, even if you keep
this as quiet as possible,

60
00:02:12,930 --> 00:02:15,180
some people will still suspect you.

61
00:02:15,180 --> 00:02:16,807
It's like those TikToks that say,

62
00:02:16,807 --> 00:02:18,517
"I won't tell anyone when I become rich,

63
00:02:18,517 --> 00:02:20,400
but there will be signs."

64
00:02:20,400 --> 00:02:23,280
This means you'll become far
more likely to get robbed,

65
00:02:23,280 --> 00:02:25,680
sued, blackmailed, or scammed.

66
00:02:25,680 --> 00:02:27,510
Once people know you have a bit of money,

67
00:02:27,510 --> 00:02:29,220
they descend like vultures.

68
00:02:29,220 --> 00:02:31,380
Trust me, I've experienced it.

69
00:02:31,380 --> 00:02:33,810
They say this is because
money changes people.

70
00:02:33,810 --> 00:02:35,220
However, over my years,

71
00:02:35,220 --> 00:02:37,890
I've realized that money
actually just reveals

72
00:02:37,890 --> 00:02:39,510
who that person really is.

73
00:02:39,510 --> 00:02:42,030
The only person you should
tell is an attorney.

74
00:02:42,030 --> 00:02:45,180
Make sure you get a good one
that specializes in trust

75
00:02:45,180 --> 00:02:46,230
and estate planning.

76
00:02:46,230 --> 00:02:48,480
A trust can save millions in taxes

77
00:02:48,480 --> 00:02:50,664
and provide a healthy layer of privacy.

78
00:02:50,664 --> 00:02:53,910
(light upbeat music)

79
00:02:53,910 --> 00:02:56,520
A lot of people will tell
you not to quit your job.

80
00:02:56,520 --> 00:02:58,320
However, I disagree.

81
00:02:58,320 --> 00:03:00,450
If your job isn't
bringing you satisfaction,

82
00:03:00,450 --> 00:03:01,800
then quit the job.

83
00:03:01,800 --> 00:03:04,230
Don't quit working, but quit that job.

84
00:03:04,230 --> 00:03:06,210
You could even wait for the perfect moment

85
00:03:06,210 --> 00:03:08,407
when your boss is pulling
a power trip, like,

86
00:03:08,407 --> 00:03:10,140
"You need to step up your game

87
00:03:10,140 --> 00:03:11,760
if you want to continue working here,"

88
00:03:11,760 --> 00:03:13,530
and then quit gloriously.

89
00:03:13,530 --> 00:03:16,620
But please go and find another
job that you actually enjoy,

90
00:03:16,620 --> 00:03:17,700
at least for a bit.

91
00:03:17,700 --> 00:03:19,920
When people quit working entirely,

92
00:03:19,920 --> 00:03:22,080
all they have to think about 24/7

93
00:03:22,080 --> 00:03:23,970
is how they're gonna spend their money.

94
00:03:23,970 --> 00:03:26,250
Many end up starting a random business

95
00:03:26,250 --> 00:03:27,720
they know nothing about

96
00:03:27,720 --> 00:03:30,660
because they're bored and
now have the money to do it.

97
00:03:30,660 --> 00:03:32,370
Some people even buy restaurants

98
00:03:32,370 --> 00:03:34,980
and end up on Gordon Ramsay's
"Kitchen Nightmares."

99
00:03:34,980 --> 00:03:36,150
Being rich and bored

100
00:03:36,150 --> 00:03:38,610
is a really dangerous situation to be in.

101
00:03:38,610 --> 00:03:40,530
The way I've always thought of it is,

102
00:03:40,530 --> 00:03:43,110
if you're working, then
you're not spending.

103
00:03:43,110 --> 00:03:45,240
So keep your life as normal as possible

104
00:03:45,240 --> 00:03:46,890
for at least six months.

105
00:03:46,890 --> 00:03:49,350
You need to process having all this money

106
00:03:49,350 --> 00:03:51,825
and not give in to the
temptation of spending it.

107
00:03:51,825 --> 00:03:54,960
(suspenseful music)

108
00:03:54,960 --> 00:03:56,580
You might think this doesn't matter.

109
00:03:56,580 --> 00:03:57,600
You're rich now,

110
00:03:57,600 --> 00:03:59,520
why worry about a few little debts

111
00:03:59,520 --> 00:04:02,130
when you could pay it
off if you wanted to?

112
00:04:02,130 --> 00:04:04,110
Well, these debts can quickly start

113
00:04:04,110 --> 00:04:05,460
eating into your fortune,

114
00:04:05,460 --> 00:04:06,570
and before you know it,

115
00:04:06,570 --> 00:04:07,740
you'll be left with nothing.

116
00:04:07,740 --> 00:04:11,220
Focus on paying back your highest
interest rate debts first.

117
00:04:11,220 --> 00:04:13,260
The main culprit here is credit cards.

118
00:04:13,260 --> 00:04:16,200
These often have 20 to 30% interest rates,

119
00:04:16,200 --> 00:04:17,520
which eat away at your money

120
00:04:17,520 --> 00:04:19,590
faster than almost anything else.

121
00:04:19,590 --> 00:04:22,080
Then you have car loans
and personal loans.

122
00:04:22,080 --> 00:04:24,630
These are worth clearing
if the rates are high.

123
00:04:24,630 --> 00:04:26,340
Finally, you have mortgages.

124
00:04:26,340 --> 00:04:27,360
Paying off their house

125
00:04:27,360 --> 00:04:29,160
is often one of the first things people do

126
00:04:29,160 --> 00:04:30,990
after suddenly becoming rich.

127
00:04:30,990 --> 00:04:34,080
However, this might not
actually be the best idea.

128
00:04:34,080 --> 00:04:37,500
If it's cheap debt, I'm talking 2 to 3%,

129
00:04:37,500 --> 00:04:40,680
it might be smarter to
keep it and invest instead.

130
00:04:40,680 --> 00:04:43,050
This is because you should be
able to get a better return

131
00:04:43,050 --> 00:04:44,160
from your investments,

132
00:04:44,160 --> 00:04:46,740
and that will offset the amount
that debt is costing you.

133
00:04:46,740 --> 00:04:49,170
So focus on clearing
that high interest debt.

134
00:04:49,170 --> 00:04:50,970
It's a guaranteed return,

135
00:04:50,970 --> 00:04:53,460
unlike investing which can go up and down.

136
00:04:53,460 --> 00:04:54,360
Paying off debt

137
00:04:54,360 --> 00:04:57,150
is the same as earning that
interest rate risk-free.

138
00:04:57,150 --> 00:04:59,310
So use this as a reset button,

139
00:04:59,310 --> 00:05:01,200
and once you're out of high interest debt,

140
00:05:01,200 --> 00:05:04,091
promise yourself never to
fall back into that cycle.

141
00:05:04,091 --> 00:05:07,200
(dramatic upbeat music)

142
00:05:07,200 --> 00:05:09,150
When you become rich all of a sudden,

143
00:05:09,150 --> 00:05:10,740
the people closest to you

144
00:05:10,740 --> 00:05:12,990
often feel entitled to a share of it

145
00:05:12,990 --> 00:05:14,340
because in their mind,

146
00:05:14,340 --> 00:05:16,800
you didn't earn it with honest hard work.

147
00:05:16,800 --> 00:05:18,390
They'll start asking for loans

148
00:05:18,390 --> 00:05:20,460
that they often don't intend to pay back

149
00:05:20,460 --> 00:05:22,890
or even come up with genius business plans

150
00:05:22,890 --> 00:05:24,270
they need you to invest in.

151
00:05:24,270 --> 00:05:25,380
Trust me when I say

152
00:05:25,380 --> 00:05:27,840
the fastest way to lose family and friends

153
00:05:27,840 --> 00:05:29,100
is to lend them money.

154
00:05:29,100 --> 00:05:30,330
Just don't do it.

155
00:05:30,330 --> 00:05:32,340
They may resent you a
little in the moment,

156
00:05:32,340 --> 00:05:33,930
but they'll get over it.

157
00:05:33,930 --> 00:05:36,630
That's far better than
getting into a messy situation

158
00:05:36,630 --> 00:05:38,100
where everyone falls out.

159
00:05:38,100 --> 00:05:41,040
But what if you want to
help out family and friends?

160
00:05:41,040 --> 00:05:42,780
Well, I have a simple rule:

161
00:05:42,780 --> 00:05:44,850
If someone I know asks me for help

162
00:05:44,850 --> 00:05:46,710
and they genuinely need it,

163
00:05:46,710 --> 00:05:48,030
then I give them the money

164
00:05:48,030 --> 00:05:52,260
and don't expect to ever be
paid back on one condition.

165
00:05:52,260 --> 00:05:54,060
They never ask me for money again.

166
00:05:54,060 --> 00:05:55,440
- [Staff] Can I have
some money then, Mark?

167
00:05:55,440 --> 00:05:57,480
- No, you're joking in. I pay you plenty.

168
00:05:57,480 --> 00:05:59,100
I recommend you do the same

169
00:05:59,100 --> 00:06:00,810
because you don't want people using you

170
00:06:00,810 --> 00:06:02,490
as their emergency fund.

171
00:06:02,490 --> 00:06:03,870
If you help them out once

172
00:06:03,870 --> 00:06:05,850
and they know they can come back for more,

173
00:06:05,850 --> 00:06:08,490
they're less likely to be
responsible with their own money

174
00:06:08,490 --> 00:06:10,800
because they know you just
bailed them out again.

175
00:06:10,800 --> 00:06:13,350
I know this point sounds quite heartless,

176
00:06:13,350 --> 00:06:15,240
but it's really the opposite.

177
00:06:15,240 --> 00:06:18,420
Sometimes you have to be cruel to be kind.

178
00:06:18,420 --> 00:06:20,310
This will save you far more friendships

179
00:06:20,310 --> 00:06:22,473
than just being someone else's piggy bank.

180
00:06:22,473 --> 00:06:26,130
(tense upbeat music)

181
00:06:26,130 --> 00:06:27,990
When most people get rich quickly,

182
00:06:27,990 --> 00:06:30,300
they still have a consumer mindset.

183
00:06:30,300 --> 00:06:32,340
They look at the money
sat in their bank account

184
00:06:32,340 --> 00:06:34,860
and think about all the
ways they're gonna spend it.

185
00:06:34,860 --> 00:06:36,240
My son's friend's family

186
00:06:36,240 --> 00:06:38,460
actually won the lottery
when he was younger,

187
00:06:38,460 --> 00:06:39,600
and his parents went out

188
00:06:39,600 --> 00:06:42,480
and bought a new house
worth over $10 million,

189
00:06:42,480 --> 00:06:43,890
a couple of sports cars,

190
00:06:43,890 --> 00:06:46,080
and sent all their kids to private school.

191
00:06:46,080 --> 00:06:49,110
Only two years later, the dream collapsed.

192
00:06:49,110 --> 00:06:51,750
Curtis' friend was yanked
out of private school,

193
00:06:51,750 --> 00:06:53,460
sports cars were sold off,

194
00:06:53,460 --> 00:06:56,910
and their $10 million home
was desperately listed

195
00:06:56,910 --> 00:07:00,210
for $6.5 million after bad improvements

196
00:07:00,210 --> 00:07:02,430
and crushing debt forced them to sell.

197
00:07:02,430 --> 00:07:03,270
This all happened

198
00:07:03,270 --> 00:07:06,150
because they didn't
understand the golden rule:

199
00:07:06,150 --> 00:07:09,120
Never spend the principle,
only the interest.

200
00:07:09,120 --> 00:07:11,220
You should be trying to grow a money tree

201
00:07:11,220 --> 00:07:13,590
that produces new income every month,

202
00:07:13,590 --> 00:07:15,840
not cutting it down
for temporary firewood.

203
00:07:15,840 --> 00:07:18,150
That's where your freedom figure comes in.

204
00:07:18,150 --> 00:07:21,450
Work out exactly how much
income you need each year

205
00:07:21,450 --> 00:07:23,040
to live the life you want,

206
00:07:23,040 --> 00:07:25,200
then multiply it by 25.

207
00:07:25,200 --> 00:07:28,770
So if you want an income
of $200,000 per year,

208
00:07:28,770 --> 00:07:31,310
you'll need to invest at least $5 million

209
00:07:31,310 --> 00:07:32,400
of your new wealth.

210
00:07:32,400 --> 00:07:34,770
The idea is that you'll
never actually have to dip

211
00:07:34,770 --> 00:07:36,180
into the 5 million

212
00:07:36,180 --> 00:07:40,290
and be able to live on the
$200,000 of interest every year.

213
00:07:40,290 --> 00:07:42,660
Even if you haven't received
a large sum of money

214
00:07:42,660 --> 00:07:44,310
and become instantly rich,

215
00:07:44,310 --> 00:07:46,710
it's still worth working
out your freedom figure

216
00:07:46,710 --> 00:07:48,780
as it's a great target to aim for.

217
00:07:48,780 --> 00:07:53,220
The rule of 25 is based on
a 4% safe withdrawal rate.

218
00:07:53,220 --> 00:07:56,730
I personally aim to grow my
money by more than 4% though

219
00:07:56,730 --> 00:07:58,140
just to be safe.

220
00:07:58,140 --> 00:07:59,417
That brings us on to...

221
00:07:59,417 --> 00:08:02,820
(smooth upbeat music)

222
00:08:02,820 --> 00:08:04,447
The most common thing I hear is,

223
00:08:04,447 --> 00:08:06,990
"Where can I find those
kinds of interest rates?

224
00:08:06,990 --> 00:08:09,780
My account only gives me 0.5%."

225
00:08:09,780 --> 00:08:10,740
The truth is,

226
00:08:10,740 --> 00:08:12,840
you're not likely to find
the kind of interest rates

227
00:08:12,840 --> 00:08:14,550
you need for the rule of 25

228
00:08:14,550 --> 00:08:16,080
in an ordinary account.

229
00:08:16,080 --> 00:08:18,540
You need to open an investing account.

230
00:08:18,540 --> 00:08:20,520
So let's say you somehow got your hands

231
00:08:20,520 --> 00:08:23,280
on that $5 million we
talked about earlier.

232
00:08:23,280 --> 00:08:24,630
How could you invest it?

233
00:08:24,630 --> 00:08:25,650
Well, at this stage,

234
00:08:25,650 --> 00:08:28,440
it's way more about
preservation and growth.

235
00:08:28,440 --> 00:08:30,540
Of course, this does depend on your age

236
00:08:30,540 --> 00:08:32,280
and how much risk you want to take.

237
00:08:32,280 --> 00:08:33,450
But here's an example

238
00:08:33,450 --> 00:08:35,670
of how I would consider splitting it up.

239
00:08:35,670 --> 00:08:38,130
Remember, I'm not a financial advisor,

240
00:08:38,130 --> 00:08:40,080
and this isn't financial advice.

241
00:08:40,080 --> 00:08:43,230
First of all, I've put $1 million

242
00:08:43,230 --> 00:08:46,920
into a low cost total
stock market index fund,

243
00:08:46,920 --> 00:08:47,970
just like this one.

244
00:08:47,970 --> 00:08:50,940
It includes over 1,300 different stocks,

245
00:08:50,940 --> 00:08:52,530
so it's very diversified.

246
00:08:52,530 --> 00:08:56,460
Its top holdings are big
companies like Apple, Microsoft,

247
00:08:56,460 --> 00:08:58,740
Amazon, NVIDIA, and Alphabet.

248
00:08:58,740 --> 00:09:00,990
This is your long-term growth engine

249
00:09:00,990 --> 00:09:05,070
and has averaged about 9% per
year over the last 20 years.

250
00:09:05,070 --> 00:09:07,560
But future returns could
be higher or lower.

251
00:09:07,560 --> 00:09:12,000
On $1 million, that's
around $90,000 a year.

252
00:09:12,000 --> 00:09:14,790
Second, I'd put $1 million

253
00:09:14,790 --> 00:09:18,090
into a low cost total
bond market index fund,

254
00:09:18,090 --> 00:09:19,110
such as this one.

255
00:09:19,110 --> 00:09:21,120
A bond fund is a pool of loans

256
00:09:21,120 --> 00:09:23,250
you give to governments or companies.

257
00:09:23,250 --> 00:09:24,900
Instead of owning one bond,

258
00:09:24,900 --> 00:09:26,670
you own a basket of many,

259
00:09:26,670 --> 00:09:28,410
which pays you regular interest

260
00:09:28,410 --> 00:09:30,960
and is generally considered
safer than stocks.

261
00:09:30,960 --> 00:09:32,520
This should help you with stability

262
00:09:32,520 --> 00:09:34,260
in the event of a market crash.

263
00:09:34,260 --> 00:09:38,370
Broad bond market indexes have
averaged 4% returns per year.

